SIMPLE: seigniorage
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seigniorage
<hw>Seign"ior*age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>seigneuriage</ets>, OF. <ets>seignorage</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Something claimed or taken by virtue of sovereign prerogative;
specifically, a charge or toll deducted from bullion brought to a mint
to be coined; the difference between the cost of a mass of bullion and
the value as money of the pieces coined from it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If government, however, throws the expense of coinage, as is
reasonable, upon the holders, by making a charge to cover the expense
(which is done by giving back rather less in coin than has been received
in bullion, and is called ⟦ldquo⟧levying a
<qex>seigniorage</qex>⟦rdquo⟧), the coin will rise to the extent of the
<qex>seigniorage</qex> above the value of the bullion.</q> <rj><qau>J.
S. Mill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A share of the receipts of a business taken in
payment for the use of a right, as a copyright or a patent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seignioral</ent>⟦br⟧
